                <p class="mt-4 sm:mt-0 ">
                    Felipe Franco, through his artistic practice and in dialogue
                    with the cultural and everyday practices of his context,
                    searches in the rural world for those trades, ways of doing
                    or objects with a specific function that are increasingly
                    forgotten in order to question their original function, give
                    them a new meaning and experiment with them in an intuitive
                    and spontaneous way. In Nectar, attracted by one of the
                    oldest spaces of the farmhouse, which was originally the
                    kitchen of the masovers*, Felipe chooses a material, in this
                    case an esparto rope, and without knowing what exactly to do
                    with it, he begins to work with his hands through the act of
                    unweaving it, day after day, representing the work of a
                    trade and exploring the times in a rural argument. A craft
                    that may not be real, but with this action, fruit of his
                    intuition, the artist works with the material, with the
                    body, with the territory, from the interior and exterior,
                    from the unknown, charging with meaning the mere action of
                    unweaving, of undoing, of returning to the original state of
                    the material. The work of a craft, to work with the hands a
                    material, that this material is a product of the craft, is
                    an act that is repeated every day and that for the artist is
                    meditative, that which connects him conceptually and
                    physically with the place that surrounds him and the
                    elements that form it. With the will to bring this act to
                    the exterior space, Felipe Franco finds two objects that
                    catch his attention and that have different uses in the
                    rural and industrial world, but that appear to be something
                    else (ladder, cart). Franco interacts with these objects,
                    giving them a new use and thus altering their original
                    function, loading them, intervening them and relating them
                    to his body. In Espronceda we can see these intervened
                    objects and the record of these actions that are apparently
                    unproductive in the context of a productive society, but
                    that endow Felipe Franco's work with a poetic, historical
                    and aesthetic charge.
                </p>
